('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:misc:ff50ced5', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> If a business has a negative net cash flow in one month, it is definitely losing money and in serious trouble.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A negative net cash flow simply means more cash went out than came in that month — it could be planned and temporary, such as buying stock ahead of a busy season. Only sustained negative cash flow over many months becomes a serious problem.</p>", "question": "What does a single month of negative net cash flow necessarily mean?", "options": ["The business is definitely losing money and in serious financial trouble", "The business has permanently run out of cash and must close immediately", "The business has made an accounting error somewhere in its financial records", "More cash went out than came in that month — it may be planned and temporary"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card explains negative net cash flow in one month can be planned and temporary, such as buying stock ahead of a busy season — only sustained negative flow is a serious problem."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:misc:20045f63', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Cash is important to a business because it allows the business to expand and invest.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Cash is specifically important for paying SHORT-TERM debts and expenses — wages, rent, suppliers, utilities. Examiners do not award marks for answers linking cash to expansion or long-term investment, as that is the role of long-term finance.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what is cash specifically important for paying?", "options": ["Short-term debts and expenses such as wages, rent and suppliers", "Long-term investments such as buying new factories or premises", "Dividends paid out to shareholders at the end of the financial year", "The cost of a long-term expansion into new international markets"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains cash is specifically needed for short-term debts and expenses — examiners do not credit answers linking cash to expansion, which is the role of long-term finance."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:misc:a2b87c44', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> The opening balance for a month is calculated by adding up all the inflows.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The opening balance is simply the CLOSING BALANCE from the previous month — it carries straight over. It has nothing to do with inflows. Many students lose marks in calculation questions by trying to recalculate it.</p>", "question": "How is the opening balance for a month actually calculated?", "options": ["It is calculated by adding up all of that month''s cash inflows", "It carries over directly from the previous month''s closing balance", "It is calculated by adding up all of that month''s cash outflows", "It is calculated by subtracting outflows from that month''s inflows"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card explains the opening balance simply carries over from the previous month''s closing balance — it has nothing to do with that month''s own inflows."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:misc:05c90957', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A business with high revenue must have plenty of cash.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Revenue and cash are not the same. A business could have high revenue on paper but very little cash if customers are buying on credit and haven''t paid yet. This is why businesses with large order books can still face a cash crisis.</p>", "question": "Why might a business with high revenue still have very little cash?", "options": ["High revenue always converts into cash immediately upon every single sale", "Revenue and cash are simply two different names for exactly the same figure", "Customers may be buying on credit and have not yet paid for their purchases", "A business with high revenue is legally required to hold zero cash reserves"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains revenue and cash are not the same — a business can have high revenue on paper but little cash if customers are buying on credit and haven''t paid yet."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:misc:c04f6622', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Net cash flow = closing balance − opening balance.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Net Cash Flow = Total Inflow − Total Outflow. While the numerical result may sometimes appear similar, the correct formula is always inflow minus outflow. Using the wrong formula will lead to errors on calculation questions.</p>", "question": "What is the correct formula for net cash flow?", "options": ["Closing Balance minus Opening Balance", "Opening Balance minus Closing Balance", "Total Outflow minus Total Inflow", "Total Inflow minus Total Outflow"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card confirms Net Cash Flow = Total Inflow − Total Outflow; although the result can numerically resemble closing minus opening, the correct formula is always inflow minus outflow."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:1d7a770b', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Identify / State — 1–2 marks — Cash Questions: Avoid the Profit Trap", "reading": "<p>When asked to \"state one reason why cash is important\" or \"identify a use of a cash flow forecast,\" students frequently lose marks by writing answers about <strong>profit</strong> or <strong>break-even</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> In real exam papers, nearly half of all candidates scored zero on these questions by giving answers about profit and loss. The examiner''s report stated: \"The most common wrong answers were to do with being able to calculate profit and loss, or break-even.\"</p>\n<p><strong>❌ Wrong (0 marks):</strong><br><em>\"Cash is important so the business can make a profit.\"</em><br><em>\"The cash flow forecast helps calculate profit.\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>✅ Correct (1 mark):</strong><br><em>\"Cash is important to pay short-term debts such as wages and rent.\"</em><br><em>\"A cash flow forecast anticipates periods when cash may run short so the business can arrange an overdraft in advance.\"</em></p>\n<p>For \"identify\" questions, one clear, specific point is all you need. Do not write a paragraph.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what is the most common wrong answer to ''why is cash important''?", "options": ["Answers about calculating profit and loss, or break-even, instead of cash", "Answers that are far too short to contain any specific detail at all", "Answers that correctly reference a specific business named in the case study", "Answers that mention paying short-term debts such as wages or rent"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card cites an examiner''s report stating nearly half of candidates scored zero by writing about profit and loss or break-even instead of answering about cash."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:2b355803', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Calculate — 1–4 marks — Master the Three Cash Flow Formulas", "reading": "<p>All cash flow calculation marks come from just three formulas. Memorise all three and practise applying them in the right order.</p>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #4a6cf7;padding:12px 16px;margin:12px 0;border-radius:4px;\"><strong>Formula 1:</strong> Net Cash Flow = Total Inflow − Total Outflow<br><strong>Formula 2:</strong> Closing Balance = Opening Balance + Net Cash Flow<br><strong>Formula 3:</strong> Opening Balance = Closing Balance of the previous month</div>\n<p><strong>Strategy for missing figure questions:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Identify which formula the missing figure belongs to.</li>\n<li>Fill in the two values you know, and rearrange to find the unknown.</li>\n<li>Always check your answer: does the closing balance equal opening + net? If not, you''ve made an error.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>⚠️ Watch out for negative numbers!</strong> If the opening balance is −£4,700 and net cash flow is £9,500: Closing = −£4,700 + £9,500 = +£4,800. Many students accidentally add the negative sign in or drop it and get the wrong answer.</p>\n<p><strong>❌ Common Error:</strong> Working out an \"opening balance\" by adding up inflows — the opening balance just CARRIES OVER from the previous month''s closing balance.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what is a common error when calculating the opening balance?", "options": ["Forgetting to include the word ''balance'' anywhere in the final written answer", "Working it out by adding up inflows instead of carrying it over from last month", "Rounding the final opening balance figure to the nearest whole pound amount", "Writing the opening balance in units instead of writing it in pounds sterling"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card warns students often try to recalculate the opening balance by adding inflows, when it should simply carry over from the previous month''s closing balance."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:8a974f46', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse — 3 marks — The U → APP → AN Chain (Cash & Profit Questions)", "reading": "<p>For a 3-mark analyse question, you need exactly three distinct steps. Without all three, you cannot get full marks — even if your business knowledge is perfect.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1 — Understanding (U):</strong> Define or explain the concept being asked about (cash, profit, liquidity, cash flow). This <em>must</em> come first — if you skip it, the examiner cannot award the application or analysis marks.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2 — Application (APP):</strong> Use specific data or details from the case study or table. Reference actual numbers, names, or details given to you. Saying \"the business\" without referencing the specific context earns 0 for APP.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3 — Analysis (AN):</strong> State the consequence or impact on the business. It must be business-facing (e.g. affects profit, affects ability to expand, risks closure). \"Costs will increase\" alone scores 0 for analysis — you must explain WHAT THAT MEANS for the business.</p>\n<p><strong>✅ Full-mark example (3 marks):</strong><br><em>\"Cash is the money QT has in its bank account available to spend (U). QT''s closing balance has fallen from £500 to £0 over five months (APP). This means the bank may refuse to lend QT money to fund its van purchase, preventing its planned expansion (AN).\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>❌ 1-mark example:</strong><br><em>\"Cash is important. QT needs cash. If it doesn''t have cash it will struggle.\"</em> — vague, no real U, no real APP, no real AN.</p>", "question": "According to this card, why does saying ''the business'' without detail score 0 for Application?", "options": ["Application marks are never available at all in a 3-mark analyse question", "The word ''business'' is banned from ever appearing anywhere in the answer", "Application requires referencing specific data, names or details from the case study", "Application can only ever be scored after the Analysis mark has already been awarded"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains Application requires specific data or details from the case study — saying ''the business'' without referencing the actual context earns zero for APP."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:fd9bedcb', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Explain — 2 marks — Identify + Explain = 2 Marks (Not Just One Point)", "reading": "<p>A 2-mark \"explain\" question requires <strong>two separate things</strong>: an identification (1 mark) plus an explanation of how or why that point works (1 mark).</p>\n<p><strong>Formula:</strong> State the point → Then explain the mechanism or effect.</p>\n<p><strong>✅ Good answer (2 marks):</strong><br><em>\"A cash flow forecast can be used as a planning tool (1). It can be shown to a bank, helping the business to secure a loan or overdraft if a cash shortage is anticipated (1).\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>❌ Bad answer (1 mark maximum):</strong><br><em>\"A cash flow forecast is useful for planning.\"</em> — states the point but does not explain what the planning involves or why it helps the business.</p>\n<p><strong>⚠️ Examiner note:</strong> Many students correctly identified a use of a cash flow forecast but then failed to explain it — earning only 1 out of 2. Always ask yourself: \"Have I explained WHY or HOW, or have I just repeated the same point in different words?\"</p>", "question": "Why does ''a cash flow forecast is useful for planning'' score only 1 mark out of 2?", "options": ["It is factually incorrect, since forecasts are never used for planning purposes", "It is too long and includes far more detail than the question actually requires", "It fails to mention a specific business named anywhere in the case study text given", "It states the point but does not explain what the planning involves or why it helps"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card explains this answer identifies a use but doesn''t explain the mechanism — full marks require explaining HOW or WHY, not just repeating the same point."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:2b7f6ef5', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluate — 7 marks — The 4-Paragraph Structure for Evaluate Questions", "reading": "<p>A 7-mark evaluate question is broken into four specific paragraphs. Each has a different job. Write them in this order every time.</p>\n<p><strong>Paragraph 1 — K &amp; U (Knowledge and Understanding):</strong><br>Define the key concept and explain how it works in general. This earns the knowledge mark and sets up everything that follows.<br><em>Starter: \"A cash flow forecast is a statement that shows... For a business like [Name], this means...\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>Paragraph 2 — AN &amp; APP (First Point with Analysis):</strong><br>Make your first specific point, link it directly to the case study using facts/numbers, and explain the impact on the business.<br><em>Starter: \"One benefit of completing a cash flow forecast for [Name] is... because [case study detail]... This would mean that...\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>Paragraph 3 — AN &amp; APP (Second Point with Analysis):</strong><br>Make a second, different point. Do not repeat paragraph 2 — explore a different aspect or argue a counterpoint.<br><em>Starter: \"Furthermore / However, another [benefit/limitation] is... In [Name]''s case, [case study detail]... As a result...\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>Paragraph 4 — Evaluation (Justified Judgement):</strong><br>Make a clear decision, justify it with case study context, and explain why — ideally using an \"it depends on...\" condition to show sophisticated thinking.<br><em>Starter: \"Overall, I believe [the cash flow forecast is very/fairly/limited in its] usefulness to [Name] because... This is particularly important given that [specific case study detail]... However, this depends on...\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>⚠️ Warning:</strong> A conclusion that simply repeats what you said in paragraphs 2 and 3 earns ZERO evaluation marks. The judgement must go beyond the analysis — it must make a decision and justify it using context.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what happens if the final evaluation paragraph just repeats paragraphs 2 and 3?", "options": ["It earns zero evaluation marks, since the judgement must go beyond the analysis", "It still earns full evaluation marks, since the content itself remains accurate", "It earns half of the available evaluation marks as a form of partial credit", "It earns full marks provided that the paragraph is a reasonable length overall"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card warns a conclusion that simply repeats paragraphs 2 and 3 earns ZERO evaluation marks — the judgement must go beyond the analysis and be justified with context."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow:tips:f2a72039', 'business', 'business:5-5-cash-and-cash-flow', '5.5 Cash and Cash Flow', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Recommend — 3 marks — Recommend Questions: Judgement + Context + Impact", "reading": "<p>A 3-mark recommend question (e.g. \"Recommend whether cash or profit will have the biggest impact\") is structured as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>Mark 1 — Basic Judgement:</strong> State your clear decision. \"Cash / profit will have the biggest impact.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Mark 2 — Application (use context):</strong> Back up your choice using specific data from the case study. Reference actual figures, names or situation details.</p>\n<p><strong>Mark 3 — Analysis (the consequence):</strong> Explain what this means for the business going forward — link it back to the question''s focus (e.g. expansion plans).</p>\n<p><strong>✅ Full-mark example:</strong><br><em>\"QT''s cash position will have the biggest impact on its expansion (1). Its closing balance has already fallen to £0 over five months (APP), meaning the bank may refuse to lend it the £40,000 needed for the van (1). Without the loan, the expansion cannot proceed at all (1).\"</em></p>\n<p><strong>❌ Common error:</strong> Writing a general discussion of both cash and profit without making a clear decision. Examiners report that some candidates \"could not reach a decision, even in the light of being led to this question.\" A judgement without a clear recommendation earns 0.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what happens if an answer discusses both options without a clear decision?", "options": ["It scores full marks, since discussing both options shows genuinely balanced thinking", "It scores zero, since a judgement without a clear recommendation earns no marks", "It scores 2 out of 3 marks, since application and analysis are both still present", "It scores full marks provided that both options are given exactly equal space"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card explains examiners report candidates who fail to reach a decision score zero — a general discussion of both options without a clear recommendation is not enough."}'::jsonb),
